{
  "doc_id": "26039",
  "text": "SEPALLATA (SEP) genes are the E-class MADS-box genes involved in floral organ determination [CITATION_1] . The unique interaction of E-function genes and various floral organ identity genes is required for the determination of floral organs [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] . Phylogenetic analysis has revealed that the SEP subfamily is monophyletic and that multiple SEP homologs are present in distant angiosperm lineages [CITATION_5] . The first duplication occurred before the origin of the extant angiosperms, which resulted in two clades, the AGL2/3/4 (SEP1/2) and AGL9 (SEP3) clades [CITATION_6] . Subsequent duplications occurred within these clades in the eudicots and monocots [CITATION_7] . The Arabidopsis SEP gene family has four members -SEP1, SEP2, SEP3 and SEP4 -from gene duplication [CITATION_8] . Many SEP-like genes have been identified from monocots. Maize and rice have at least eight and five different SEP-like genes, respectively [CITATION_9] [CITATION_10] [CITATION_11] . However, recent findings of SEP-like genes in monocots were mainly restricted within the Poaceae.",
